Amnesty International focuses on domestic issues

By Donna Pesansky

- Staff‘ Writer

Amnesty International began its annual
Human Rights Week by shattering the
dominant myth that human rights viola-
tions are absent from the United States.

“Usually Amnesty International looks
at political prisoners in Guatemala, South
America and South Africa, but tonight it’s
important to make people aware that
issues facing America prisoners are bad
and are getting increasingly worse,” Jane
Anderson said in her speech last night
on “Race and the Politics of Justice: The
Case of Mumia Abu-Jamal.”

Anderson is the coordinator of the
Washington-based Quixote Center cam-
paign on “Equal Justice U.S.A.,” which
works to provide human rights in the
U.S. Criminal Justice System.

The United States entered the ‘90s with
more people in jail than anywhere else
in the world and more people of African
descent than anywhere in the world.

Anderson said there are more young
African-American men in jail than in col-

lege, and it is five times more likely for J

an African-American man to be in jail in
the United States than in South Africa.

Anderson defines political prisoners,
or prisoners of conscience (as Amnesty
International terms them), as people
who are victims of racism and the eco-
nomic and political situation in which
they are forced to live.

An example of this injustice was seen
in 1982 when Mumia Abu—Jamal, an
African-American journalist responsible
for covering police misconduct, was con-
victed of killing a Philadelphia police
officer and is now on death row.

“[Abu—Jamal’s] trials were full of injus-

ltices,” Anderson said. “He defended him-

self but was never allowed in the court-
room because he intimidated jurors,
according to the judge.” She said the jury
consisted of 10 white and two African-
Americans, and Abu-Jamal was-only
allotted a total of $150 to make his case. -

And the biggest wrong-doing against
Abu—Jamal was when the prosecuting
attorney mentioned in court that 10
years prior to this incident, Abu-Jamal
was a member of the Black Panther
Party, which was notorious for defend-
ing itself and its neighborhood against
police, Anderson said.

Anderson said this point was brought
up during appeals, but it was still con-
sidered admissible evidence. She noted
a similar case in Delaware where a man
convicted of homicide was affiliated with
a white racist group, and his case was
dismissed.

“This is a double political view where
views of a white racist are protected,
but black militants’ aren’t,” Anderson
said.

Anderson concluded by saying “unless
more people start organizing activities to
make people aware, the universal
climate is not going to turn around.”

