Democratic deﬁciency

The potential was there. For the first time since Teddy
Roosevelt formed his splinter Bull Moose Party in 1912,
America had a serious third-party candidate — H. Ross Perot.
Dismissed by much of the media as a freak of nature, Perot
faced an uphill battle ever since his emergence on the scene.

Much of the criticism was  A total revamping of the
government, Perot said, is what is necessary for this country
to work again. As such, this little man with the big ears
proved to have dictatorial tendencies. But had Perot not re-
entered the race the the candidates surely would have
ignored the deﬁcit issue. Despite the fact that he Wasn’t the
best man to carry the important message of political reform,
in recent times Perot proved to be the most successful. It
wasn’t so much that 19 percent of the population voted for
him, as it was that they voted against the alienation that
occurs under a two—party system.

Last night in Washington, D.C., the seeds of reform planted
by Perot were given-a little sunlight, and the roots fertilized
once again. Members of “third parties” all over the country
met to discuss what they could do to increase political repre-
sentation in America. Unfortunately, the success of the Perot
candidacy and lack of success of the Libertarian party (a legiti-
mate third party in its own right) proves that little can be
done nowadays unless one has the proper financial
resources.

Third—party representation is something that has been “out
there” since the beginning of our government but has met
with little success. This is due, in part, to the archaic manner
in which presidential candidates are elected. The electoral col-
lege was established in order to keep a check on the “igno-
rant masses.” Since electoral college votes are based on a
“winner—take—all ethic” it is virtually impossible for third parties
to get the proper recognition.

SecEjn”clly;“tl1‘e’media ‘themselves have to take a greater
responsibility. As one reader pointed out to us, the
Pennsylvania senatorial election is a perfect example. The
Associated Press reported that Lynn Yeakel and Arlen Specter
accounted for 100 percent of the votes cast. Yet, at the same
time, the Libertarian candidate John Peny was reported as
having received 5 percent of the popular Vote. Clearly this is a
contradiction. The media are supposed to remain “objective,”
in their reporting. All too often we ignore things that should
be recognized. 4

Sometimes we holler reform too quickly, and the results are
often devastating. But that old political standby —- the two-
party system —- has proven to be constipated. The riots in Los
Angeles showed the world that, irrespective of what party has
been in power, the wishes of many Americans are pushed
aside. Surely in a country of 270 million people, a third party
will do little to change the alienation which occurs.
Nevertheless, it will do something. We know that you “can’t
satisfy all of the people all of the time,” but this conference
will hopefully be the stepping stone toward greater participa-
tion.

